description.text:
The Trudeau table is a small side table designed to sit between two chairs. The materials required are about about half a sheet of 3/4" plywood, plus two larger pieces of wood for the top (or make your own top from plywood or another material).

The joints are cut with 0.02" clearance on all sides. In practice, this means they are snug, but you can slot them together by hand. They are intended to be sanded flush and glued in place (the legs are attached with finishing nails and glue). There is no cutting profile for the top included in the design (it's just the crosspieces and legs). I used a pair of pieces of reclaimed 2x12" Douglas fir (about 19" long) for the top of my table, but you're supposed to choose a piece of wood that's meaningful to you. You attach the top with long wood screws.

There are two toolpaths in the included VCarve file: one which cuts a collection of circles at 0.1" deep to mark where to put hold-down screws and one to make the profile cuts for the pieces. In the picture of the plywood in the cnc machine above, you can see the circles for the screws. The weight of the plywood was sufficient to hold things in place for the screw-locating circles (at least for me).

I used a 1/4" upcut end mill (Onsrud 65-025). This worked nicely-- though the top edges were a little fuzzy, they cleaned up instantly with a little sandpaper.
Since the table was going outdoors, I finished it with Watco Teak Oil, which makes a nice water-resistant finish. The plywood wasn't exterior-grade, but I'm not too worried-- for the past five years, the side table has been a cardboard laser printer box with a blanket on it! (I'll update in a year or two to note how everything performed in practice.)

The files included are ordered sort-of-logically:

1) If you use VCarve, I've included the whole project laid out as a .crv file. Note that my 3/4" plywood was actually 0.78" according to my calipers, so the cut depth is 0.78. You should check your material and reset this before exporting toolpaths.

2) If you use another CAM program, I've included just the cutting vectors as dwg and dxf files (exported from Rhino). You'll have to work out hold-down yourself, as this doesn't include the screw-locating circles.

3) If you want to alter the basic design, I've included the original Rhino file, which has a 3d model of the table as well as the cutting paths.

I've also included some conversions to 3d modeling files in case you want to 3d print a scale model of the table (note: the tabletop is not attached in the model), or remix this for another use.

This is a pulley system I designed to allow for a more precise, printed mechanism to operate the eyes of Crow, the sassy robot from Mystery Science Theater 3000.  
It works well with my Crow, but if anyone has any issues with the radius on the wheel, you can hack it up, or ask me and I can upload a different size on it. It's a Work In Progress at the moment, input on improving it is welcome!  Don't mind the globby glue. I was putting this together to test the mechanisms, not ready for golden pretty paint yet!
Credit for Crow himself goes to Best Brains Inc. The design is mine as an improvement over the styrene-in-dowel system I've seen online.  
12/14/2015 - Majorly updated it to address issues I've experienced with the old one that was on here. The rotation wasn't optimal and wouldn't allow him to roll his eyes back properly. I also put a cutout in the main bracket so it can be swapped out without having to cut the string.
MCCLOUD!

I printed these at 0.2mm height, 2-3 shells, 20-30% infill. Everything is hidden anyways so favor structural strength over aesthetics.
Print out A, B2, and C. A should compression fit onto the longer peg of the B2 piece. B2 should fit onto C with a bolt or something to allow it to rotate. Drill/cut holes in the ping-pong balls for the pegs in A to fit into. The pegs are sized to 38mm (the official size of the eyes), so in theory a 38mm ping-pong ball will have the peg hit the opposite side to help you center it. A larger ball should just tilt to the side when they hit each other since the walls of the ball are so thin. The puppet string of your choice is then laced through the holes in B2. I like to drape the string over the top groove in B2, and loop it through each of the inner holes, up through the outers, and back down the inner holes to create a sort of knot. You could also take two strings and tie one to each side, it's really your choice and I tried to make it a simple design with multiple options. The strings feed through the C plug which is then glued into the CPVC pipe. My Crow is designed so the C plug goes into a 1/2" CPVC pipe. It is not a tight fit, so a bit of glue keeps it in place (this is so the plug isn't ever too big if you go with a tighter ID pipe).

This is a protective case for the 8Bitdo Zero GamePad.

The 8Bitdo Zero GamePad is a miniature bluetooth Gamepad controller for iOS, Android and Windows. It is designed to be portable and as such needs protection from dirt and scratches while being carried.

description.text:
I've changed to a Chimera and I got this for sale now.
£13+PP for the two printed parts with the piezo fitted, the cooling pipe and the four M3 bolts and one M3 Nut.
If interested message me here or on Facebook https://www.facebook.com/messages/t/makinbug

UPDATE 01 Sept '17

  • added a fan shroud
  • the legs of part b are now touching part a. That makes the hot end more stable when cornering at very high speeds.

Leadinglights, Moriquendi, ( http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?1,635075,page=1 ) DjDemonD and others ( https://www.duet3d.com/forum/thread.php?id=752&p=1 ) have spent many hours developing what is, arguably, the lightest and most precise bed leveling probe available as of June '17.
Here are some of the ways you can use a piezo as a nozzle z-probe:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2069480
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2319993
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2117069

This is a remix of Idris's ( Moriquendi) effector here https://www.duet3d.com/forum/thread.php?pid=10329#p10329
I liked his idea because it offsets the nozzle and you don't lose in printing height.
It works with 3x 15mm piezo disc z-probe, Huntley's magnetic arms spaced at 64mm ( other mag arms will work) and Berd-Air cooling.

Also see 64mm Magnetic Carriages here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2371707

You will need:
1x Piezo probe board ( PM Moriquendi on the RepRap or Duet3d forums) or make your own https://www.dropbox.com/sh/3q38ew98kt7f8sq/AAB_uA6tQL2ETlGcnfdijm2Ra?dl=0
3x 15mm piezo discs ( search Murata 15mm piezo ) each with an M3 brass nut soldered to the back
1x M3x15mm bolt
3x M3x35mm bolts
1x M3 nut
6x M3 Nylon Nuts for the spheres

It should print without supports but be cautious when sliding the piezo in place. Use a soldering iron to melt the plastic if you need to make some room for them.
First thing I've placed a dab of E6000 where the wires are soldered to make sure they will stay put. I like the E6000 because is strong but easy to remove if need be.

Part a, the triangle, should face the z tower with the Bert-Air hole. Part b should be mounted with the fan facing z tower. All the wires are also facing z tower.
If part b is printed accurately the 35mm bolts should rotate freely and not exit more than 1.8 mm down the bottom.

I hope the pictures are complementing my instructions well enough.

To mount, fit the metal spheres first then slide the piezos in their place and using the M3x35mm bolts gently attach part b to the piezos. Not too tight. Center them in place, then glue them as they are using E6000, superglue or the like. When dry, secure the wires with more glue and connect them in parallel to a connector of your choice. I've used the pins from a JST connector.
When all is dry, dismantle part b and slide the hotend in it, pass the wires from the bottom of part a, then connect them to the hotend and bolt the fan with the wires facing down. Place part b back on the piezos and bolt it using needle nose pliers to hold the brass nuts. Use little force and make sure the piezo is not moving when tightening.
Rotate the hotend for the wires to face the Bert-Air hole, then secure it with the 15mm bolt.
Use a 2mm cable tie to secure the wiring loom to the hotend.

For setup details please read DjDemonD post here https://www.duet3d.com/forum/thread.php?pid=7726#p7726 or here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2069480

To that, I would add the following:
-on my Duet digital mode doesn't work, only analog with VR1 at 11 and VR2 at 4 o'clock
-I probe on .8mm PEI, bull clipped to on top of a 6mm al bed, at 210c hotend and 65c bed. I've tested the hotend 220c for 3 seconds and it leaves no marks on the PEI.

Caution: for some reason probing on PEI glued with 3M 468MP to aluminum plate gives high inconsistencies. I guess is because 468MP is 0.125mm thick and gives a bit under pressure. I the future I would use 3m 467MP which at just 0.05mm, should make for a harder surface.

-I've got a -0.15 z offset in my config file and the trigger value is 500 ( G31 X0 Y0 Z-0.15 P500 )

Any questions please contact me
Enjoy

We all know that the A8 acrylic frame is way too flexible. I was inspired by Photoberto's thing (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2351450) which uses M6/M8 rod to add torsional support to the front of the frame. After installing that upgrade I noticed a flex in the frame across where the LCD runs. So I designed these plugs to fit in the A8 cable management holes and to accept an M8 threaded rod. These plugs along with some M8 rod and some large washers give rigidity to the vertical supports, preventing them from flexing inwards. A printable alternative does exist (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2176224), however I prefer the strength of threaded rod and not wasting so much time printing an upgrade that may be weak.

I'm happy to modify for other rod sizes if need be. Feedback also welcome.

  • Maple leaf

description.text: This is a scale model of an actual table we built in class. The idea is to be able to show the different components needed to help illustrate the thinking required to pull off a project like this.

Identify the Challenge

The students were annoyed that the class coffee table, was small, old, rickety and inadequate. One student put forward a design for a table that would make use of some left over wood.

Empathy Map

We did a little math, and drew some scale drawings to ensure that we had the right dimensions. We also worked with other students to select a height that would suit a laptop.

Purchase Supplies

We did need some extra supplies that our school Makerspace couldn't supply. In all it cost 60$ to have just enough.

Prototype

We built it in the classroom with a circular saw and a drill motor. There was one major dimension challenge given the access to the fir trim wood we were able to purchase and so we had a quick redesign on the fly.

Pilot

Once in place, the students were incredibly positive and appreciative. One student 3D designed a plaque for the side to commemorate the project.

Curate

It's important (in our class anyway) that we finish by sharing the story. Part of that was creating the 3D Design for the table, and sharing this on Thingiverse.

Electronics Mounted Inside Electricals:

Inside, you'll need to put electronics and an actuator to make the device move and speak.

The model is designed to interface with a Tower MG90s servo.

I used a Arduino Pro Mini clone to drive the servo and an audio playback module.

I used this to play the audio: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01E3B0PG0/ref=crt_ewc_title_srh_2?ie=UTF8&psc=1&smid=A26ATEC08S9EFM

You'll need some 2mm dia self tapping screws and a few washers to assemble the joints. Everything else, bodge together with hot melt.

A resonance chamber will help the volume from the speaker. I just used the top of bottle that was laying around, but you could probably print a better one if you were so inclined.

I mounted a AA battery holder on the back, and used a 5v boost to drive the electronics. Check the voltage and current requirements of your arduino, audio module and servo, and supply accordingly.

The servo runs a 30 degree sweep with 15ms between degree steps. I'll provide some example code.

Code

Here's what I used to drive the arduino:
Note that the code features an unused button function to have it activated for a short loop via pushbutton instead of turn-on-leave-on

/* BILLY-SHERMANATOR by JON HANFORD
This code exists under CC BY-NC-SA 3.0, So you can use it - but be respectful. 
https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/
Tips are always welcome, btc: 1L9XDQ3fMa1LRFg9UEKZpCgN3kc6tdS5TS
*/

#include <Servo.h>

Servo myservo;  // create servo object to control a servo
// twelve servo objects can be created on most boards
const int  buttonPin = 2;    // the pin that the pushbutton is attached to
const int playPin = 10;   // the pin that the audio module is attached to
const int delayVal = 15; // servo speed adjustment
const int servoMin = 75; // servo minimum pos
const int servoMax = 105; // servo maximum pos
const int annoyLoops = 7; // how many arm waves are we doing per button press

int pos = 0;    // variable to store the servo position
int count = 0;  // variable to store the loop number
int buttonState = 0;         // current state of the button
int lastButtonState = 0;     // previous state of the button
void setup() {
  myservo.attach(9);  // attaches the servo on pin 9 to the servo object
}
void annoy() {
  count = 0; // init the counter
  while (count < annoyLoops){ // run this loop the specified number of times
  digitalWrite(playPin, HIGH); // turn on the audio module
  for (pos = servoMin; pos <= servoMax; pos += 1) { // goes from min degrees to max degrees
    // in steps of 1 degree
    myservo.write(pos);              // tell servo to go to position in variable 'pos'
    delay(delayVal);                       // waits spec time for the servo to reach the position
  }
  for (pos = servoMax; pos >= servoMin; pos -= 1) { // goes from max degrees to min degrees
    myservo.write(pos);              // tell servo to go to position in variable 'pos'
    delay(delayVal);                       // waits spec time for the servo to reach the position
  }
  count = count + 1;    // increment that counter
  }
  digitalWrite(playPin, LOW); // turn off that racket for the love of god. 
}
void readTheButton(){
      // read the pushbutton input pin:
  buttonState = digitalRead(buttonPin);

  // compare the buttonState to its previous state
  if (buttonState != lastButtonState) {
    // if the state has changed, run the annoy function
    if (buttonState == HIGH) {
      annoy();

    // Delay a little bit to avoid bouncing
    delay(50);
  }
  // save the current state as the last state,
  //for next time through the loop
  lastButtonState = buttonState;
  }
}
void loop(){
  //readTheButton();
  annoy();

}

title: Lm6uu PLA bushing bearing for 1/4” rod with small contact area

description.text:
These are printed PLA bushings that will fit an lm6uu pillow block, but ride on 1/4” hardware-store rod for cheap experimentation. (these are a lower-load, lower-friction version of these: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2351281 ). I wanted to minimize contact-ares for lower friction/stiction for lower-load use, and I wanted to be able to print these without internal support… these fit the bill.

Although it is not necessary, because of the smaller contact area I anneal these in a toaster oven at 175 degrees for about 30 minutes (let them cool down gradually in the oven before removing them). That hardens the surface a bit more so they don't quickly wear out, and they are less likely to heat up from friction and become chattery. I use a small aluminum bread pan covered loosely with foil to keep the surface from getting too cooked. if you plan to anneal them, print with higher density infill (but not 100% since you might end up with uneven voids that will do wonky things, you want the air pockets to be able to move around a bit) .

The dimensions will change slightly after cooking, so you may not have to use a hot rod to prep them, depending how much they shrink (usually about 0.2mm-0.4mm inner diameter). SideNote: after cooking, these should shrink down to a size where they will run on 6mm rail pretty nicely as well, but they may wear loose quickly, so print them at a slightly smaller scale if you plan to do this.

Then use the prep instructions for my quickie lm8uu bushings here ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2322548 ). Always keep the rails lubed up with silicone spray to keep them from binding (which also somewhat seals the surface against absorbing humidity and changing the dimensions and friction coefficient).

description.text:
NOTE: I have successfully printed this, I just forgot to take a picture of it before I sent it off! If you print this, please share an "I Made One" post and, if I reprint this, I'll post one for sure.

I designed this print with money in mind, specifically for donating to the Seattle Children's Hospital through 3D Printing Nerd and his #HighFive tag! Here are Joel's awesome YouTube and Patreon sites:

https://www.youtube.com/3DPrintingNerd
https://www.patreon.com/3dprintingnerd

It would be trivial for me to make different versions of this - with different text, with no text - so just let me know in the comments if you'd like a special version.

This holds five, clean US bills perfectly. If you go to the bank, make sure you ask them for clean/new(er) bills. If printing with supports, just use a metal pick to dig them out of the corners and sides really well. The bills wouldn't fit until I got all the little support pieces out.

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Medium

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I used supports with this, because although some printers, with certain settings, can handle extreme overhangs like the corner- and side-holders, I didn't want to risk it. If you print with supports, you're going to have to use a standard metal pick to dig all the little pieces of plastic out, or the money won't slide in easily. Trust me, it looks way cooler if you take the time to dig the plastic out!

This is also a good test to see if your bed is perfectly level. When I printed this, the left-front was a little lower, and I could see that in the resulting print on the bottom. Not a big deal, but if you don't have a good level, this print may act weird with curling, or whatever.

Also, I used PVA (purple, kids') glue stick to great effect. It's my favorite go-to for most prints. It cleans off well, and does a decent job - with good leveling - to give perfect, even bed adhesion.

Corner- and Edge-Holders

If you print with supports - and I highly recommend that you do - you will need to get in there with a metal pick and dig out all the little support pieces. If you're careful, you won't break the supports. You should be able to slide five, clean US bills in there. If they won't fit, you aren't done cleaning out the holders yet! I ended up doing the digging on a darker placemat, so I could see all the little white PLA curls as I pulled them out. Progress!

Fusion 360 and Simplify3D

I love Fusion 360! And Simplify3D does a great job of slicing, supports and the like. I used fairly basic geometry, offsets, extrusion and embossing. Used the standard Arial Rounded MT Bold typeface, even though I have access to hundreds (thousands?) of TypeKit fonts with my Adobe Creative Cloud account. Arial is just a nice typeface and it prints well, easy to read at most sizes. This is my first time making the "holders" and I had a lot of fun figuring out how to do this. There may be an easier way, but I'm learning as I go along.

US (American) dollars have the following specs:

Width 6.14 inches ≈ 156.1 mm
Height 2.61 inches ≈ 66.3 mm

You don't have to just put money in this...just 1-5 pieces of regular paper of these exact-ish dimensions.

description.text:
Track kit for 1/5 Scale Maxstone Crawler.

Added a second servo to give the crawler four wheel steering and made a short video (poor quality) of the crawler: https://youtu.be/zoORonerMSM

Printer:

multiple printers used

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

25

Notes:

Printed with multiple printers. I printed all parts in PETG. Other material required for each track pod assembly:

2 of 6807-2RS bearings (for drive sprocket)
10 of 625-2RS bearings (two for each idler)
5 of M5 x 65mm bolts (one for each idler)
4 of M5 x 16mm bolts (tension adjustment)
9 of M5 locking (Nylock) nuts (tension adjustment and idlers)
4 of M5 flat washers (tension adjustment)
2 of M3 x 20mm (for shaft clamp)
2 of M3 locking (Nylock) nuts (for shaft clamp)
3mm ABS filament - used to attach the track link segments together

For Anti-rotation of track pod assembly:
4 of M3 x 10mm bolts
4 of M3 locking (Nylock) nuts
4 of M3 flat washers
2 of M5 nuts (used for anti-rotation bracket attachment)
1 of M4 x 14mm bolt (longer bolt for axle steering knuckle Bolt 98073)
1 of 1/8" aluminum plate, 1" x 25mm (bolts to bottom of axle steering knuckle)
2 of 15mm lengths of 1/2" aluminum U channel (bottom spring attachments)
2 of 851631 Hillman Compression Spring (3-1/4" x 13/16", 82.6mm x 20.6mm)
Some 150 pound test down rigger stainless cable
Butt splices used to secure the down rigger cable

For each track pod, will need five idler wheels, one drive sprocket, two side plates, and two idler adjust plates. The 'L' and 'R' in the part names designate for the Left or Right side of the Vehicle. 'O' or "Outside" and "I" or "Inside in the part names designate if the part is on the frame side of the pod (Inside) or away from the frame (Outside.) Will also need two of the shaft lock parts.

Assembly:
If you find the 6807 bearing fits a little loose (all printers are a little different), add a couple wraps of Kapton tape around the mount for the bearing or the bearing, as required.

Mount the bearings in the idler wheels. I used a bolt and nut to pull the bearings in place inside the idler wheels. Mount the bearings in the drive sprocket. Mount the idler adjust plates to the two side plates.

Slide the inside plate over the axle shaft. Mount the nuts into the two shaft clamp parts. Use a piece of Kapton tape to help hold the nuts in place. Hold the two shaft clamp parts on the shaft (axle adapter 59016) while mounting the drive sprocket on to the axle. Ensure the two 3mm bolt holes in the drive sprocket align with the nuts in the shaft clamps. Try to push the shaft clamps into the inside hex hole in the drive sprocket while getting the drive sprocket over the hex shoulder on the axle adapter (easier to do than describe.)

Start the two M3 x 20mm bolts through the two 3mm holes in the drive sprocket (easier to start the bolts before installing the drive sprocket) until the start to engage the nuts in the shaft clamps. Ensure the drive sprocket is fully on the shaft and tighten the two M3 x 20mm bolts. Put the original wheel hub nut on the axle. I put the rough side outwards as do not want it wearing out the PETG plastic. The drive sprocket should now be fairly rigid on the drive axle. Push the inside plate into the bearing on the inside of the drive sprocket.

Should be able to mount the outside plate on the drive sprocket. The five idler wheels can now be attached. Tighten the M5 x 65mm bolts until fairly snug and back off until the idler wheels spin freely (half to one turn of the bolt.)

Track:
With my printer, I required 49 track links per pod. The holes in the track links are two different diameters. The side of the track with three holes has slightly smaller holes - clean these out with a 3mm drill bit. Hold two track links together, interlocked, and push a length of 3mm abs filament through until it comes out the other side. There should be a little bit of a friction fit going through the three holes on the one side of the track link. If your printer prints the holes a little too large, you will need to melt the ends of the abs filament with a soldering iron to flatten out the end so it does not slide through the track links.

Anti-Rotation:
I used what I had available or could easily get. You may have to improvise if you can not get similar parts. You will need four of the Spring Cap parts per pod. Print two of the Guide-60mm parts - these help hold the springs compressed with about 10mm between the insides of the Spring Cap parts while the springs/caps are being secured in place.
Easier to install the spring parts with the tracks removed.

The Maxstone Crawler does not go very fast. Have not noticed any heating of the motors. Turning radius leaves a lot to be desired! Crawler should be upgraded to four wheel steering.

Uploaded a modified version of the track link without the grouser portion. If every second track link does not have a grouser on it, will make it easier to for the track to get a grip to climb over things, though this could be harder on the gears/drive train.

title: V-rail extrusion slider carriage for 20x20 extrusion

description.text:
( See https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2365103 for a simplified 2-piece variant of the replaceable-slide-surface version ).

Yet another cheap linear motion thingie for experimenting. This is a slider carriage to ride on 20x20 aluminum v-rail extrusions (i.e. OpenBuilds.com ). I have been using these and they work well for prototyping, or just getting your kinematics together before eventually replacing them with v-wheel gantry carriages. I have no data on long-term use though. Print either 2x one of the solid models and bolt them together with m3 or 4-40 screws, or mix and match the replaceable sliders (print 4x ‘A’, and then 2x ‘B’, and then 2x either B, C or D.). Two types of spacers are provided to adjust the width (wider base = more stability and less likelihood of binding) if you don't want to make a custom spacer for sizing and mounting, etc.

All the sliders I have seen have large contact patches to increase the load capability, but these are meant to be free-moving with light loads. They have adjustable preload/wear-compensation to balance the amount of play against the amount of ‘stickiness’ since I tried to make a small contact area so that these slide easily but smaller contact patch = faster wear = more play, so an m3 nylon-insert locknut and M3 screw can be used to press the flexible contact plate against the rail. These won’t take a heavy load or much misalignment, but even in those designs, they may work for prototyping. I am currently using these to prototype an ultimaker-style kinematics system.

There is also a version that has replaceable parts that can be replaced without having to slide the whole carriage off the end of the rail (which usually would necessitate disassembly of the rail mounting assembly, which is annoying). The parts hold together fine once bolted together, but you could use a dab of superglue in the corners to hold it together if you want, and then just snap it apart when you have to replace it. Sandwiching a slider_spacer_block.stl between 2 replaceable sliders make assembly easier.

Try one out to see how the tolerances are, and If they printed too tight after you screw them together or your printer rounded off the contact surfaces, use a small file on the 8 contact points to flatten them out a bit, and then run the carriage back and forth until it moves freely (with a bit of play since you can snug them up with the preload screws).

There are also three sub-versions of each, which use different mounting options (in case you don’t want to print a mount to bolt between two sliders): solid, wood screw, machine-screw + nut.

As usually with printed PLA slide bushings, print a trial version until you are happy with the tolerance you get from your settings, then print the rest. Slip them on a rail and slide them up and down a bunch until they glide smoothly or even a bit loosely (since you can snug them up with the preload screws). These run on the inner V section of the extrusions, so keep that area lubed up with heavy silicone spray.

Assembly video for the replaceable version here: https://youtu.be/gmRHukSal1s just snap together and use small wood screws to secure.

author: flyinriz

title: The Original VeNect Maker Mould Cotton Swab Size
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The VeNect Maker Mould is a tool for creating VeNect Connectors out of sculptable materials like clay. A VeNect Connector is a Vector Equillibrium Intersection Point that rods and dowels can be inserted into. It can be used to build a tetrahedron (4 VeNects), a Vector Equillibrium (13 VeNects) or anything composed of the Isometric Vector Matrix Geometry. This mould specifically is for the shafts of cotton swabs, but it can be resized to accommodate any size of dowel or rod.

Included in this distribution is the original STL file that can be resized in any software that supports the format, and a 3w file with supports that is print ready on any printer that supports the format.

After I designed the Original VeNect Connector, I was a little disappointed at how long it took to print the components, and how much filament I was using to print each part. So I started brainstorming how I could make more connectors a lot quicker. I designed about a dozen prototypes before creating this universal mould. It took another week or so of experimenting to figure out the best material to use, and the best manufacturing process for making accurate parts. In the end, I found that plastic sculpting clay, or model magic seemed to work best. For sculpting clay, I invented this process:

https://youtu.be/b5-Dy30_pbs

For model magic, you just insert cotton swabs into the mould as seen in the pictures, and wait a few days for it to dry. If you want to make 10 at a time, just print off 10 copies of the mould. If you want to make 100 at a time, print off 100 copies, etc.
